# Filemark — Chrome Web Store publishing credentials
#
# Copy this file to `.env` (same directory) and fill in the four values below.
# The Taskfile auto-loads `.env` for any `task cws:*` / `task release` command.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. CWS_EXTENSION_ID
#    The extension ID from the Chrome Web Store developer dashboard.
#    Found at: https://chrome.google.com/webstore/devconsole  →  your item  →
#    the 32-character ID in the URL (e.g. abcdefghijklmnopabcdefghijklmnop).
CWS_EXTENSION_ID=

# 2. CWS_CLIENT_ID + CWS_CLIENT_SECRET
#    OAuth 2.0 credentials from Google Cloud Console.
#    Steps:
#      a) https://console.cloud.google.com/  →  create (or pick) a project.
#      b) APIs & Services  →  Library  →  enable "Chrome Web Store API".
#      c) APIs & Services  →  Credentials  →  "Create Credentials"  →
#         "OAuth client ID"  →  Application type: "Desktop app".
#      d) Copy the client ID and client secret into the two vars below.
CWS_CLIENT_ID=
CWS_CLIENT_SECRET=

# 3. CWS_REFRESH_TOKEN
#    A long-lived refresh token for the OAuth client above. Generate once:
#
#      npx --yes chrome-webstore-upload-cli@3 refresh-token \
#        --client-id "$CWS_CLIENT_ID" \
#        --client-secret "$CWS_CLIENT_SECRET"
#
#    That command prints a URL — open it in the browser, sign in with the
#    Google account that owns the Web Store listing, approve, and paste the
#    code back. The tool prints the refresh token; copy it here.
CWS_REFRESH_TOKEN=
